SIMPLE: snip
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Snip
<hw>Snip</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Snipped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Snipping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[D. <ets>snippen</ets>; akin to
G. <ets>schnippen</ets>.]</ety> <def>To cut off the nip or neb of, or to
cut off at once with shears or scissors; to clip off suddenly; to nip;
hence, to break off; to snatch away.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Curbed and <qex>snipped</qex> in my younger years by fear of my
parents from those vicious excrescences to which that age was
subject.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The captain seldom ordered anything out of the ship's stores . . .
but I <qex>snipped</qex> some of it for my own share.</q> <rj><qau>De
Foe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Snip
<hw>Snip</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A single cut,
as with shears or scissors; a clip.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small shred; a bit cut off.</def>
<rj><au>Wiseman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A share; a snack.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>L'Estrange</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A tailor.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark> <rj><au>Nares.
C. Kingsley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Small hand shears for cutting sheet metal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snipe</ent>⟦br⟧
